<br>
-Druids weren't intended to get ports, they pretty much put them in to use the Stonehenge type structures. Verant has admitted this. This kinda threw Wizards a real curveball IMO. <br>
<br>
-Enchanters originally didn't have an animation pet, this was added after initial release.<br>
<br>
-Magician pets were not initially released with spell casting abilities. I'm not sure about their inherent resistances at the time either. <br>
<br>
Other evidence also points to a haphazard fast fix approach of some classes. The one good example I can give recently was the quick release of the 60 heal spell on the test server. It replaced the Anti-summon shield spell within a week of it being on test. In fact, The 60 heal appeared on test roughly 2-3 days before Luclin release.. <br>
<br>
My honest conclusion of the early magician class was one that was meant to draw the UO crowd to EQ. You ask why.. Well lets see:<br>
<br>
1. Elemental Summons-Very potent spells from UO<br>
    <br>
2. &quot;Summon and WEAR armor line&quot; according to the early spell lists, and according to webpages like eq.stratics.com at the time. Along with the printed EQ strategy guilde.<br>
3. High damage nukes.<br>
<br>
It fit the classic &quot;Tank Mage&quot; that was highly popular in Ultima Online at the time. The early magician class was VERY VERY under developed compared to what we have today, suggesting that it was one a last minute class as well.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=wezloc>WEZLOC</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Master Summoner</span><br>  Posts: 167<br> <font color=#333333>(2/21/02 8:30:06 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=112.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_sunglasses.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: I don't think verant..</span><hr size=1> My only question is what makes you think mage + pet should be no greater then monk damage.  I dont agree with that because it doesnt explain why the monk class is the class we should be basing our damage balancing issues around.  Verant has never compared monk damage to mage damage and I dont know why we should either.  Also DS will have to be part of any discussion regarding mage damage. Damage shields increase damage dramatically so they cant be ignored. <br>
<br>
Also bard &quot;utility&quot; is hard to gauge because they are doing so many thing.  When you compare our best damage shield to any one of the primary bard utilities they win.  A bard giving 50%+ haste to all group members in the group is going to far exceed the damage of a damage shield.  Same goes for giving mana to casters.  The damage a caster is going to be able to do because of catana is going to far exceed the best mage damage shield very easy and very quickly. If a bard has a epic he further boost his groups damage over time and lessens there damage taken over time.  The only weakness that the bard class has is for the most part a bard cant go frontal attack on most mobs alone.  They dont have the hps or double attack to make head to head combat with a mob worthwhile.  But with combo of fear kiting or charm kiting this is easily overcome.  But then again alot of the more uber bards on my server go head to head with mobs all the time without needing to fear kite.  I think everyone would do themselves well to see some of the weapons a bard can wield.  Bards can wield some of the fastest weapons in the game. Moving them to the same damage table as warriors helped alot. Along with increasing weapon skills.  Bards can come very close to or equal mage damage in raids. Even more so if no pet is being used.  If we add the damage increases that bards are giving to there group then they are even more off the charts.  <br>
<br>
One last thing if a mage is going to say BoB make them able to outdamage any bard.  They should look at what weapon a bard is going to be wielding. You have to compare apples to apples.  If mage has BoB then the bard has to have comparable equipment. There is a bard I know with a 16/19 1hb weapon that procs a 250dd spell. He has a dex of 238 without even playing a song.  With that in the primary hand and epic in the offhand he is outputing major damage. He procs 6 to 7 times on average per fight. All those factors have to be added in. Melee can upgrade damage in many ways. Casters are way to limited. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ubalanzsonofanz.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Balanz son of Anz</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Abuser of EZCodes</span><br>  Posts: 861<br> <font color=#333333>(2/21/02 4:01:15 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=112.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_exclamation_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Damage: Monk &gt;= Mage + Pet &gt; Bard</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> I don't think verant has a balancing process to be quite honest.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I agree.  But we can establish <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> bounds</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and say <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;beyond this bound is unbalanced.&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
For example, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Charm</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> forms an upper bound on pet power.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Charmed</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> pets are more inconvenient than <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Summoned</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> pets, and so there should be some benefit.  While one could argue that this might or might not be fair, I think no one seriously believes that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Verant</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> would give <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> a generally available summoned pet that was better than the best creature that could ordinarily be charmed.<br>
<br>
In the absence of clear principles or measurements, attempting to establish bounds may be the most useful thing we can accomplish in analyzing class balance and remedies.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Other evidence also points to a haphazard fast fix approach of some classes.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->There is too little <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> quality control</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> on <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Verant</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->'s part, and they do not take full advantage of what little there is.  Far too often, changes do not even make it to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Test</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> before they are released.  At best, one change is put on <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Test</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, flaws discovered, and the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;fixed change&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> goes directly to <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Live</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, having never been tested.  Several managers deserve pink slips for these shoddy development processes, although I doubt they will get them.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> My only question is what makes you think mage + pet should be no greater then monk damage.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Upon reflection, there is an unstated assumption here, namely that pathing risks will be reduced at some point so that the norm is that pets are available with nominal risk.  In that case, the question is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;What is an <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>adequate</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> level of damage dealing to assure third and subsequent Magicians a place in most raids?&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  I conclude that no more than a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Monk</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->'s damage is adequate, and hence forms a reasonable upper bound.<br>
<br>
If we neglect the risk that pets entail for the moment, the utility of a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magician</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> would seem to me to be at least as much as that of a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Monk</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  What does a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Monk</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> bring to the table?  Damage Dealing, Modest Tanking and Pulling.  Did I miss anything?  Assuming a tank and a puller, then subsequent <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Monks</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, like subsequent <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> are mostly valuable on raids as <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> damage dealers</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  However, the surplus <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magician</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> still brings at least as much utility to the table as the surplus <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Monk</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  The ability to churn out rods when a fight as gone bad is worth at least as much as a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Monk</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> tanking in an emergency.  From this I conclude it would be unfair to deal more damage than a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Monk</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
A <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Warrior</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> at least is a perfectly adequate alternate tank if the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Main Assist</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> goes down, and may thus save the entire raid.<br>
<br>
Finally, we have the services of an active <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Monk</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> who posts regularly to this board and shows interest in our issues.  At the very least, this makes a good starting point.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Also DS will have to be part of any discussion regarding mage damage. Damage shields increase damage dramatically so they cant be ignored.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->On the contrary, they <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>must</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> be ignored for this discussion.  Only the <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>first</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magician</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> can claim credit for damage shields, and this discussion revolves around subsequent <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magicians</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  In addition, damage shields are clearly <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>group</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> support.  If for the sake of clarity, we omit the additional damage dealt through group support songs such as <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Haste</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, we must ignore damage shields for the same reason.<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> If a bard has a epic he further boost his groups damage over time and lessens there damage taken over time.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->As stated above, and in the original post, boosts to the group's damage are counted under utility, not damage.  This simplifies the analysis enormously.<br>
<br>
I agree that the analysis of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Bards</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is complicated.  To simplify things, I think the following assumptions are reasonable.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 1)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> There are other bards doing the most important raid songs already.<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 2)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> The bard is meleeing.<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 3)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> The bard is twisting four songs, two of which are support, and do not count except as self buffs, and two of which focused either directly on the enemy or on the bard himself.<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 4)</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> The bard has raid level equipment.<br>
<br>
I will freely confess to knowing little about <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Bards</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> except what I have observed in groups and raids, and I welcome all contributions, especially <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Wezloc</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->'s, who seems to have a great deal of experience with <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Bards</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.<br>
<br>
