<br>
Which all exist on armor in one form or another <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Beside the ability to pull, the primary thing a Monk brings to the table is damage dealing. Magicians bring more than that.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Monks bring:<br>
Massive damage.<br>
Pulling (this takes more then one monk for big pulls, up to 3 really)<br>
Ability to take over as tank.<br>
Corpse recovery.<br>
Scouting.<br>
<br>
Their secondary and tertiary abilities are all more powerful then our own support. Tanks are always needed, pulling is always needed. We beat them numerically.. but practically?<br>
<br>
You have to consider how often you need to summon a waterstone. Is it convinient? Sure I guess. But, how often do you need to pull? Daily, several times a day..<br>
<br>
See how that works? I don't believe it's fair to compare Magician and Monk utility. Monks exceed us to to demand for their utility.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Therefore Monks doing less damage than Magicians in groups or raids seems likely to be unfair.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Not to me.<br>
<br>
This game is supposedly about balance. No class is strictly better then another.<br>
<br>
You have three basic types of archetypes:<br>
<br>
Priest.<br>
Melee.<br>
Caster.<br>
<br>
Each of these archetypes is generally well balanced against the other.<br>
<br>
Warriors have the best hp/ac, and can thus tank the best. They have powerful offense as well, which means they are good damage dealers. However, they have no variety, no flexibility. A warrior is tank, or a secondary damage dealer.. and very very rarely a puller. He's completely dependant on those around him, and on his gear, to do the job.<br>
<br>
SKs/Paladins suffer slightly less ac/hp, but make up for it with their spells. Paladins represent strictly defensive, while SK's represent the offensive aspect. Both have superior taunt to a warrior, and easier time travelling, and greater variety over all. They also provide inferior damage over all. <br>
<br>
Rangers provide equal damage, but far less tanking ability then warriors. They also have a variety of spells for ease of travel, and general support functions.<br>
<br>
Rogues and Monks are on the opposite end of the spectrum from warriors. Both have sub-par defense, but make up for it with superior offense. Monks, because they have slightly greater defense, have slightly lesser offense. <br>
<br>
Each of these classes, in respect to eachother, is balanced. Each gives a little, and gets a little.<br>
<br>
Priests are also balanced in respect to one another.<br>
<br>
Clerics represent the extreme end of the support spectrum. Their damage capabilities are sub-par, not even mediocre. They couldn't kill their way out of a wet paper bag, so to speak. But, they make up for it in the form of incredibly powerful buffs, and the best heals in the game by far. They are vital to efficiency. <br>
<br>
Clerics = Warriors. Specialization over Variety.<br>
<br>
Shamans are in the middle. They have decent buffs, decent heals, and provide good damage in the form of nukes and dots. And the best slows/debuffs in the game.<br>
<br>
Call shamans the Knights. Utility and flexibility over specialization.<br>
<br>
Druids represent the more damaging side of support. Their dots and nukes represent a great deal of damage capabilities. <br>
<br>
Druids are the rangers. Larger damage capabilities, mediocre buffs, mediocre heals.. equal damage and support really.<br>
<br>
Intelligence casters are also balanced in relation to one another.<br>
<br>
Wizards are the undisputed kings of the nukes. I think they need a little positive tweaking pre-50, but that's another discussion. They can check against more resists then anyone else, they have lures, and unresistable nukes. They have great defense in the form of root and snare, shadowstep and evacs.<br>
<br>
Wizards are like the warriors. They have a lot of offense, and a lot of defense.<br>
<br>
Enchanters are much more defense oriented then the other int casters. Root, mes, charm, stun, fear, haste, slow. They are there to more indirectly effect the battles. They allow others to do THEIR best, instead of contributing directly.<br>
<br>
Enchanters are like Knights. They, like warriors, sacrifice the ability to do a great deal of direct damage, in order to allow others to function at THEIR peak. They also have an incredibly diverse arsenal of spells at their beck and call. Enchanters are not all played the same. Some prefer charms, some single mes, some AoE mes, some stun locking.. lots of room for individuals.<br>
<br>
Necromancers are quite possibly the most diverse of all the int casters. They can root, mes, snare, fear, dot, DD, pull, heal, twitch, and tap. They do pay a price though, that of being KOS in many places, and having little stackability. I believe the stacking issues should be done away with, and a way to allow multiple necros to stack multiple dots on the same target. Imagine 20+ necro dots all eating away at a mob. A single necro can do warrior + damage in a single fight if they have a good raid going that can manage aggro.<br>
<br>
I believe they should be doing monk damage, as they should pay a price for their incredibly diverse and powerful defense and support.<br>
<br>
Magicians are the extreme of the int casters. Like wizards, we can unleash a great deal of damage in a short period of time. We also have vicious pets to add to our over all damage over time. However, we pay a price for this. We have literally no intelligent defense available to us, and our utility generally comes significantly later then other classes. We are specialized in offense, and penalized in defense, as it should be.  This balance was upset somewhat with Kunark. With the addition of Call of the Hero and Mod Rod, our true purpose was muddied. We took a hit in offense, to have these more supportive roles. But, we got no corresponding raise in defense at all.<br>
<br>
So, we are like rogues. Lots of offense, slight defense, and limited and situational utility.<br>
<br>
But, right now I don't believe OUR balance is achieved. We either need a raise in offense, or a raise in defense.  <br>
<br>
This is why I have no troubles thinking we should be doing rogue-type damage.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> While under some circumstances one will clearly outdamage the other, and under other circumstances, the reverse might be true, I remain convinced that this is a worth while starting point for discussion.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It is.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Please look me in the eyes and say &quot;Verant will make Magicians the equal of Rogues in damage output, as it is only fair.&quot;<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I can, and will, for the reasons stated.<br>
<br>
Intra-Archetypal balance is achieved. However, Inter-Archetypal balance is still skewed. Melee's are a little too powerful, priests are just right, and casters are a little feeble.<br>
<br>
Of course, raising the power of magicians should also come with a corresponding raise in the power of all int casters but level 60 Wizards. (Before that they so definitely need some tweakage)<br>
<br>
Anyway, that's how I feel. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=wezloc>WEZLOC</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Master Summoner</span><br>  Posts: 175<br> <font color=#333333>(2/22/02 10:52:46 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=112.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_smile.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Hmm</span><hr size=1> Pulling<br>
Tanking<br>
Corpse Recovery<br>
<br>
These are three of the most powerful skills in the game. The game is structured around these things. Without a monk or a rogue corpse recovery would be horrid. There are alot of experience zones that if you dont make it out you will need a rogue or monk to pull corpses. Same for raids. Without them you going to be spending a ton on coffins.<br>
<br>
Also FD is one of the most powerful abilities in the game.  I rank it in the top 5 of most powerful abilities in the game.<br>
<br>
Snare<br>
Mezz<br>
Slow<br>
Stun<br>
FD<br>
<br>
I really cant think of any 5 skills that I would place above those 5. Out of those top 5 skills/spells mages have neither. Also note I didnt even list rezzing, sow, or teleports. When you compare a monk to a mage you have to compare the entire pie.  It is very easy to say well all they do is pull and CR.  Well those are very powerful abilities.  Damage shields are nice but dont rank anywhere near pulling and CR abilites, neither does CoTH.  <br>
<br>
I would trade CoTH for FD or snare any day of the week and twice on Sunday.  Tanking is another ability that cant be replaced by summoned arrows or summoned anything.  Pets dont make good tanks. They have low ac and very low overall resist.  I guess I am having a hard time seeing your point.  Monks might not have as many &quot;utilities&quot; as mages. But they have by far more important ones. Dont think many groups/raids would take damage shields over a main tank. Or CoTH over a monk FD pulling.  When you weigh the skills that melee have, many of them far out pace magicians in overall utility.  <br>
<br>
Do to the thurg gate potion quest a ton of post 50 melee can gate for free.  Being able to bind anywhere isnt even a issue, because post 50, even more so post 55 a cleric is going to be in your group to rez you.  I have played 2 melee classes post 50 and binding isnt a issue at all.  Invising is a joke since all higher lvl zones have mobs that see invis. In kunark most mobs see past invis as a rule. I normal am never invis, and it is one of my least used spells.  Most of our summons are on melee uber loots.  I think you should lay out what utilities you think add great value to the mage class then compare them to monk abilities/utilities and see where it balances out.  I think you will find monks come out way ahead.<br>
<br>
The only good utility mages have is mod rods.  It is a great skill and makes encounters alot easier then they would be without rods.  Other then this I dont really see alot of mage usefulness. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/utemuriksnacks.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Temurik Snacks</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mage</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#333333>(2/22/02 12:44:41 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=112.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_smile.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Hmm</span><hr size=1> Nonsense. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/utemuriksnacks.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Temurik Snacks</A> at: 2/22/02 12:45:11 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ueuripedmoped.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Euriped Moped</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Arch Mage</span><br>  Posts: 465<br> <font color=#333333>(2/22/02 10:09:28 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=112.topic&index=14>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yolora/zdance.gif height=40 width=40></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_smile.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Hmm</span><hr size=1> Like I said before, verant HAS to have SOME system they use to determine the value of each ability a class has.<br>
