<br>
As for the variety of circumstances, well, I think we look at some log parses and get some <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;rubber numbers&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> that approximate the numbers we are getting.<br>
<br>
For example, we might assume that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Magician</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> spell damage is resisted two-thirds of the time, and the pet procs are resisted half.  Melee damage can be approximated from several fights, maybe even simplifying AC as a <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;resist&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> per cent of potential melee damage.<br>
<br>
Then once a simple model is working, we can go back and add in some of the factors that were simplified or ignored.<br>
<br>
This is done in physics all the time.  For example, solving differential equations involving <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> sin x</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> do not yield simple polynomials.  So instead, physicists often take advantage of the fact that when <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> x ~= 0</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, then <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> sin x ~= x</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  They trade in all their <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> sin x</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->'s for <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> x</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->'s, and all of a sudden they are back in polynomial land, which is much easier to deal with.  Then after they've done all their reasoning, they go back and see how well their approximation holds.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Raz</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
